events.description: At the behest of Tsar Peter the Great, the construction of Kadriorg Palace, dedicated to his wife Catherine, begins in Tallinn.

events.description: Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart completes his Symphony No. 40 in G minor (K550).

events.html: • 1792 – The Brunswick Manifesto is issued to the population of Paris promising vengeance if the French royal family is harmed.

events.html: • 1797 – Horatio Nelson loses more than 300 men and his right arm during the failed conquest attempt of Tenerife (Spain).

events.description: War of 1812: An American attack on Canada is repulsed.

events.description: Costa Rica annexes Guanacaste from Nicaragua.

events.description: James Bowman Lindsay demonstrates a constant electric light at a public meeting in Dundee, Scotland.

events.description: Joaquin Murrieta,  the famous Californio bandit known as the "Robin Hood of El Dorado", is killed.

events.description: The Wyoming Territory is established.

events.description: The Japanese daimyōs begin returning their land holdings to the emperor as part of the Meiji Restoration reforms. (Traditional Japanese Date: June 17, 1869).
events.html: • 1869 – The Japanese daimyōs begin returning their land holdings to the emperor as part of the Meiji Restoration reforms. (Traditional Japanese Date: June 17, 1869).

events.description: The First Sino-Japanese War begins when the Japanese fire upon a Chinese warship.

events.html: • 1915 – RFC Captain Lanoe Hawker becomes the first British pursuit aviator to earn the Victoria Cross.
